properties.name: MS001
properties.desc: The Mount Si Trailhead, is expansive, with room for dozens of cars. Head north of the parking area and cross over a small creek to start the hike. If you need to fill up with potable water at the spigot.

properties.name: MS002
properties.desc: The trail comes to a junction with the Talus Loop Trail, which traverse up Mt. Si the opposite direction and eventually meets back up with the Mt. Si Trail. This route adds about a mile to the trip, but can be a nice alternative to the crowded Mt. Si trail. Go left to continue on the Mt. Si trail.

properties.name: MS003
properties.desc: At 1600ft arrive at a rocky overlook where the forest opens up views to the south of the Rattlesnake Recreation Area, and Mt. Washington. A nice place for a rest.

properties.name: MS004
properties.desc: A small creek parallels the trail on your right as you approach a junction with the connecting end of the Talus Loop Trail. Head left to continue on the Mt. Si Trail.

properties.name: MS005
properties.desc: At about 2000ft arrive at Snag Flat, an small plateau with burned douglas firs that keep the evidence of the 1910 Mt. Si wild fire. A small boardwalk and interpretive sign commemorate the area.

properties.name: Boardwalk
properties.desc: The boardwalk at Snag Flat winding through douglas firs.

properties.name: Barren Stands
properties.desc: The landscape becomes dark and closed in with stands of 2nd growth and a barren forest floor.

properties.name: MS006
properties.desc: Leading downhill and due South is much steeper, but shorter Old Mount Si Trail. Continue heading uphill to the top.

properties.name: MS007
properties.desc: Follow the trail signs to this expansive overlook named Snoqualmie Point. The view is vast, looking west all the way past Seattle to the Olympics.

properties.name: Haystack
properties.desc: A view of the Haystack from below the start of the scramble

properties.name: Snoqualmie Point
properties.desc: View of the valley west from the point.

properties.name: Scramble
properties.desc: Hiker braving snow on the scramble up the Haystack.

properties.name: Scramble Rest
properties.desc: Taking a rest on the way up the scramble

properties.name: MS008
properties.desc: For those willing to assume the risk, the true summit is attained by scrambling to the top of the massive rock haystack. Be warned, this is a very dangerous scramble, and every few years a life is claimed from accidental falls from the top. Once on top the view becomes 360 degrees stretching north to Mt. Baker, and South to Mt. Rainer.

properties.name: Summit
properties.desc: Looking down the very top at a happy hiker and the valley 3500ft below.

properties.name: View East
properties.desc: Looking east at I90 snaking between Mailbox Peak and Mt. Washington.
